The steps below encompass the standard pre-processing workflow for scRNA-seq data in Seurat. These represent the selection and filtration of cells based on QC metrics, data normalization and scaling, and the detection of highly variable features. The script then breifly shows how to cluster cells, identify differentially expressed genes and remove noise.

Quality control

The percentage of reads that map to the mitochondrial genome is a common quality control metric. These are not noted on the non-model Atlantic cod genome as in human/mouse genomes. So I have used grep function on the annotated genome to create a list of existing genes (mithochondrial_gene_names.txt) which have the word mitochond in their protein name

mt.list<-read.table("mithochondrial_gene_names.txt", header=F) # the list of mithochondrial genes from GadMor3
mt.list<-unlist(mt.list$V1)
mt.list<-mt.list[mt.list %in% rownames(merge_seuratfish)] # Find those that are in the seurat object
all(mt.list %in% rownames(merge_seuratfish)) # Just to make sure that the previous line worked
## [1] TRUE
#mt.list # See which genes are represented in the data

merge_seuratfish[["percent.mt"]] <- PercentageFeatureSet(merge_seuratfish, features = mt.list, assay="RNA")

Filtering based on QC metrics

merge_seuratfish_filtered <- subset(merge_seuratfish, subset = nFeature_RNA > 150 & nFeature_RNA < 1500 & nCount_RNA > 200 & nCount_RNA < 4000 & percent.mt < 5)

##Normalisation and selecting variable features This script demonstrates the process of normalizing data and identifying variable features independently for each dataset using Seurat. The resulting variable features are then selected for integration across datasets.

#To construct a reference, we will identify anchors between the individual datasets. First, we split the combined object into a list, with each dataset as an element.
fish.list <- SplitObject(object = merge_seuratfish_filtered, split.by = "treatment")
# normalize and identify variable features for each dataset independently
fish.list <- lapply(X = fish.list, FUN = function(x) {
    x <- NormalizeData(x)
    x <- FindVariableFeatures(x, selection.method = "vst", nfeatures = 2000)
})

# select features that are repeatedly variable across datasets for integration
features <- SelectIntegrationFeatures(object.list = fish.list)

##Perform integration

We then identify anchors using the FindIntegrationAnchors() function, which takes a Seurat objects as input, and use these anchors to integrate the datasets together with IntegrateData().This allows cells from the same cell type/subpopulation to cluster together, despite being exposed to different treatments or coming from different batches.

# This chunk is time consuming. By incorporating 'cache = TRUE option', you can minimize the time spent on re-executing unchanged or successfully executed portions of your Rmarkdown document.


immune.anchors <- FindIntegrationAnchors(object.list = fish.list, anchor.features = features, verbose = FALSE)

# this command creates an 'integrated' data assay
integrated_seuratfish <- IntegrateData(anchorset = immune.anchors, verbose = FALSE)

Determine the dimensionality of the dataset

To overcome the extensive technical noise in any single feature for scRNA-seq data, Seurat clusters cells based on their PCA scores, with each PC essentially representing a metafeature that combines information across a correlated feature set. The top principal components therefore represent a robust compression of the dataset.

# original unmodified data still resides in the 'RNA' assay
# Set the default assay for the Seurat object 'integrated_seuratfish' to "integrated"
DefaultAssay(integrated_seuratfish) <- "integrated"

# Scale the data in the 'integrated' assay of 'integrated_seuratfish'
integrated_seuratfish <- ScaleData(integrated_seuratfish, verbose = FALSE)

# Run Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the scaled data
# 'npcs = 50' specifies the number of principal components to compute
# 'verbose = FALSE' suppresses verbose output during PCA
integrated_seuratfish <- RunPCA(integrated_seuratfish, npcs = 50, verbose = FALSE)

The Elbow plot ranks of principle components based on the percentage of variance explained by each one

ElbowPlot(integrated_seuratfish, ndims = 50)

There is no clear elbow on this plot, so several dimensions were tried in downnstream UMAP and DEG analysis before settling on 45 dimensions.

##Dimension reduction and clustering the cells

# RunUMAP: Runs UMAP (Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection) to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset
# 'reduction = "pca"': Uses principal components obtained from PCA (Principal Component Analysis)
# 'dims = 1:45': Specifies the dimensions to be used for UMAP (in this case, the first 45 principal components)
integrated_seuratfish <- RunUMAP(integrated_seuratfish, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:45)
## Warning: The default method for RunUMAP has changed from calling Python UMAP via reticulate to the R-native UWOT using the cosine metric

# FindNeighbors: Identifies neighboring cells based on the reduced dimensions (e.g., PCA)
# 'reduction = "pca"': Specifies the reduction method to use (PCA in this case)
# 'dims = 1:45': Specifies the dimensions to be used for finding neighbors
integrated_seuratfish <- FindNeighbors(integrated_seuratfish, reduction = "pca", dims = 1:45)
## Computing nearest neighbor graph
## Computing SNN
# FindClusters: Performs clustering on the dataset based on the identified neighbors
# 'resolution controls the granularity of the clustering; smaller values result in more clusters
integrated_seuratfish <- FindClusters(integrated_seuratfish, resolution = 0.24)

Making a list of differentially expressed genes (DEGs) per cluster in order to identify cell type

#This command identifies the DEGs in cluster 0 in comparison to all other clusters
cluster0.markers <- FindMarkers(integrated_seuratfish, ident.1 = 0, logfc.threshold = 0.25, test.use = "roc", only.pos = TRUE)

#Print the top 20 most significantly DEGs
top10_genes <- head(cluster0.markers, 10)
print(top10_genes)

Gene analysis determines that cluster 2 expressed TCR genes, Ig genes, hemoglobin genes etc, suggesting this is not a true cell cluster.

# This violin plot shows the average number of transcripts expressed per cell within each cluster
VlnPlot(integrated_seuratfish, features = c("nCount_RNA"), group.by = "seurat_clusters", pt.size = 0)

The DEGs and the violin plot of number of transcripts per cluster together suggest cluster 2 actually represents ambient RNA captured from empty beads in the wet lab process and should be removed from further analysis.

# Filter out cells in cluster 2
cleaned_seuratfish <- subset(integrated_seuratfish, subset = seurat_clusters != 2)
